<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900608-0021</DOCNO><DOCID>900608-0021.</DOCID><HL>   Technology:   IBM Computer Centers   Planned in Eastern Europe   ----   A Wall Street Journal News Roundup</HL><DATE>06/08/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   IBM EUROP</CO><IN>COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)</IN><LP>   International Business Machines Corp. said it plans to setup computer centers in Hungary and Czechoslovakia, inconjunction with academic institutions, to advance technologyand initiate research projects.   IBM Europe will provide the centers with advancedhardware, a library of systems and application software, andtraining and education for the staffs. It plans to lend thecomputer equipment to the countries, including an IBM3090-model mainframe priced at about $1 million, a spokesmanfor the Armonk, N.Y.-based company said.</LP><TEXT>   This represents the first part of a broader initiative IBMplans in Central and Eastern Europe to fosterinformation-technology advances and give scientists andothers access to tools to communicate in their fields orparticipate in international projects. The centers will belinked by a Vienna computer gateway to Western academicnetworks.   Setting up the centers is subject to export licenses beinggranted by the U.S. and the Coordinating Committee onMultilateral Export Controls. IBM said the Hungarian andCzechoslovak partners will sign a document that states theend use of the computers will be for peaceful purposes.   Once established, the IBM centers will be staffed andoperated by the local IBM partners, for access by academics,students and people in industry. IBM's partner in Hungarywill be the University of Economics in Budapest; inCzechoslovakia, Charles University and the Czech TechnicalUniversity.</TEXT></DOC>